Cyberpunk is 80's inspired wish fulfillment about a crapsack future where the sort of corporations that led to the term "banana republic" run daily life.

As such a popular sport in a Cyberpunk world would have to fulfill the needs of the genre. It should be violent, because one of the core features of any Cyberpunk I've ever seen is that violence is rampant and nobody gives a fuck (it's part of the wish fulfillment). It's that typical, and condescending, "bread and games" attitude. Right now we keep people glued to the tube with fat guys running into each other (just ignore baseball, basketball, real football, etc.), so turn that up to 11. Next up it should be profitable for the corps. So it should need a lot of material to be played. Helmets, padding, special gear, etc. And it should be eminently merchandisable, though that goes for any sport that's popular enough. They've found merchandise of popular gladiators, for fuck's sake.

And loud. It should be very loud. Played in big stadiums, plastered on screens in public places (just not all of it, you have to pay for that). "BOOM! Can you believe that play, Cotton? He just took his arm. Clean! Off! This year's Murderball Super League is shaping up AWESOME!... to remove censorship renew your Murderball license with CRAP Net. For additional content sign up for the Murder Special package, now 10% off for participants in the Impressive Headwound Contest."

The players, being both wealthy and cashcows, are probably chromed to the gills. The newest stuff, probably illegal mods that would get anyone less wealthy arrested. New players are sponsored and literally owned by corps, at least their artificial bits. There's a guy without limbs panhandling down by the station, claims to have been a pro Murderball player.

The problem with sci-fi sports is that people typically overthink it. Any popular sport is born of its circumstances. American football is popular in America, because Americans are wealthy enough to afford the gear, and it's a massive social thing. Football is popular in Brazil (and every other country that isn't in North America), because you can play it with literally only a ball. Ice hockey is popular in Canada, because it's cold there. Basketball is popular with African Americans because they live in neighborhoods where concrete courts are practical.

In short, if a sci-fi community lives on a space station, I'd expect them to have a Zero G sport. If they live on a planet, I wouldn't expect them to. If they have material wealth to spare, I'd expect them to be much more likely to participate in sports that require extra gear. If they're poor, I'd expect them to be much more likely to have space football.

You could always go the Star Trek route: We know Parisses Squares is a thing, we know it requires athletic fortitude, we know it's relatively dangerous, and we know it requires a court and minimal gear. Everything else is left to the imagination. We just know it's a future sport people like to play.
